<A HREF=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=308196 target=_blank>Magelo</A></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#778899><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/bmonklybusiness43508.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=wubao>Wubao</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Grand Master</span><br>  Posts: 1264<br> <font color=#8b1a1a>(8/10/02 2:31:38 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fmonklybusiness43508frm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1765.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: creation stats- what to do??</span><hr size=1> whatever you feel like putting your stats in will serve you just fine.<br>
<br>
With absolutely no points placed in STA, you can eventually max out your STA, your HPs and STILL have more than enough AC to survive big raid type mobs in this game. So the premium on STA isn't as pronounced as some make it.<br>
<br>
You could put all of your points into charisma and still have good stats as a monk by the time you're level 60.<br>
<br>
That being said, the stats that have the largest effect on being a monk are:<br>
<br>
1) Charisma (you can't hold much or carry much, so that extra 5 gold made off of the items you DO sell adds up over time).<br>
<br>
1) Stamina (more Hit Points keep you alive longer, even if it is just 5 or 6 more at first).<br>
<br>
2) Strength (slightly more damage output isn't noticable at level 60, but people who reccommend ALL STA somehow forget, or NEVER experienced level 1 with NO gear, and don't realize that the higher STR DOES HELP YOU KILL THAT FIRE BEETLE YOU JUST MET FOR THE FIRST TIME ... also, high str helps with smithing and as a HUMAN monk, you can smith and make GOOD money later on doing cultural armor).<br>
<br>
3) Agility (for much the same reason people who say all sta overlook str, they also overlook agility. Granted it's a statistic that is easy to raise over time. But for those first five to ten levels on your very first character, where you've got nothing but a few pieces of leather and a ton of dusty burlap or CLOTH to keep you alive the added AC from higher agility can make a difference against that Frothing Kobold hellbent on your destruction).<br>
<br>
4) Dexterity (Helps with Proc rates, and your weapon skills skill up slightly faster. Both of those advantages are minimal and come much later in life).<br>
<br>
5) WIS or INT (tradeskill advantages here. And maybe you're a monk that wants to learn all the languages? Yeah, I know, not something worth putting the points into, but my point is, you're not SUNK if you DO put them here).<br>
<br>
So yes, powergamers, or people who want to feel secure in their NUMBERS are going to say stamina, stamina, stamina all day long until they're blue in the face.<br>
<br>
But MANY a level 60 monk put their starting points into stats OTHER than stamina and they scrape by just fine.<br>
<br>
Don't stress where you put your points man. Make a monk, play him or her and have fun.<br>
<br>
